---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Me"
  description="Phil Giammattei's Exerience and Interests"
>
  <h2><em>Hi! My name is Phil Giammattei.</em></h2>
  <img src="/img/phil-tiger-pajamas.jpeg" alt="a picture of me" />
  <h2>That's pronounced</h2>
  <img src="/img/ghee.png" alt="ghee a MĀ tee" />

  <h2>Experience</h2>
  <p>
    I currently work for <a href="https://arcjet.com">Arcjet</a> as a frontend engineer,
    where I own the development and maintenance of our user-facing control panel application.
    I've gotten my hands dirty replacing legacy React code with lean and clean components
    that play to the strength of semantic HTML and CSS. Every day at a Series A startup
    is a new adventure, as we deliver requested features to users as quickly as possible,
    accelerate our workflows with AI agents, and stay on top of critical vulnerabilities.
    Every day I get to help turn beautiful designs and ambitious visions into working
    interfaces!
  </p>
  <p>
    Simultaneously, I returned to my roots as a web developer, making intensely
    handcrafted and personal web sites for myself and for clients, as part of
    the <a href="https://tigerpajamas.com">Tiger Pajamas Web Site Company</a>,
    along with my good friends
    <a href="https://ashleymcquaid.com">Ashley</a> and <a
      href="https://turningfortune.com">Jon</a
    >. We've had a lot of fun delivering beautiful, hand-crafted sites to our
    clients.
  </p>
  <p>
    Previously, I was an Infrastructure Engineer at PNC, where I built out new
    features for their Continuous Delivery Pipeline. My work helped thousands of
    software teams deploy their code, and it taught me a lot about
    containerization, standardization, and automation at an enterprise scale. I
    especially liked writing Groovy code, which is the language that should have
    been called “Java Script,” if you ask me. I also replaced an aging CLI with
    a brand new Angular/Go app, and that was a lot of fun!
  </p>

  <p>
    Prior to my work at PNC I was a React-on-Rails developer at
    <a href="https://inventables.com">Inventables</a>, a CNC company with deep
    inroads in the consumer and small business space, improve their
    <a href="https://www.inventables.com/pages/easel">Easel</a> in-browser design/CAD/CAM
    software and helped break ground on their <a
      href="https://www.inventables.com/pages/easel-cabinetmaker"
      >Easel Cabinetmaker</a
    > product for professional cabinetmakers. I had a blast in this fast-paced environment,
    constantly exploring the space between software and physical objects and gaining
    a solid understanding of Ruby backend architecture and React state management.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before that, I was a UI Engineer for <a href="https://clarivate.com"
      >Clarivate</a
    >, a large company with many products serving important niches in the
    Information Economy. I served on an “internal consulting” team of UI
    experts, assisting in UI overhauls of legacy apps and drove initial
    development on their <a
      href="https://clarivate.com/products/ip-intelligence/assess-brand-risk-from-every-angle/"
      >Brand Landscape Analyzer</a
    >
    product. Working heavily with Angular, Gatsby, and Material components, I led
    efforts to inculcate a culture of software best practices, including code review,
    pair programming, and <a
      href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Design_by_contractContract-Driven
    Development"
      >Contract-Driven Development</a
    >.
  </p>

  <p>
    Prior to Clarivate I was at PNC in a different stint, doing Angular and
    Spring development for their <a
      href="https://www.pnc.com/en/corporate-and-institutional/asset-management-group/investment-office.html"
      >Asset Management Group</a
    >
    division. My team broke ground on a content-based microservice for their wealth
    management app that displayed external data with JavaScript-based visualizations.
  </p>

  <p>
    That was my first job after attending the <a
      href="https://www.techelevator.com/">Tech Elevator</a
    > coding boot camp. Up until then I was the Operations Manager for <a
      href="https://kerfcase.com">KerfCase</a
    >, a luxury E-Commerce shop that hand-makes phone cases machined from blocks
    of wood. Along with overseeing production, order fulfillment, and customer
    service, one of my responsibilities was maintaining and enhancing their
    site, which is built on Shopify and constitutes the company’s sole sales
    channel. I learned a lot about nitty-gritty web development here, picking up
    jQuery and the Liquid template syntax Shopify uses, along with pulling off
    some very gnarly CSS hacks to get everything looking good. I write more
    about this experience <a href="/projects/kerfcase">here</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before that, I did a lot of tech-adjacent things for a lot of tech-centered
    companies, like sales for Oracle, data analysis at Google, and all-around
    helpful presence at the Apple Store.
  </p>

  <p>
    During undergrad, I bounced around schools and majors like a pinball,
    eventually being launched from the University of Pittsburgh with a Religious
    Studies degree, with many non-applicable credit hours sunk into computer
    science and music courses. I also learned some Spanish.
  </p>

  <h2>Skills and Interests</h2>
  <p>
    My eclectic education and work history is difficult to form a coherent story
    from. Never content to commit myself to a worn path, I have consistently
    prized versatility over virtuosity and continue that tradition as a
    generalist software engineer with competencies in design, business, and
    support. I wouldn’t have it any other way.
  </p>

  <p>
    Every career experience teaches me something new. At various turns, I've had
    to act as my own manager; my own designer; my own product owner. I've talked
    directly to customers and interviewed potential leads. Recently I've begun
    learning statistics from <a href="https://deadsimpletech.com"
      >Iris Meredith</a
    >, and I can't wait to see how my studies will impact my engineering work!
    My work in large enterprise infrastructure taught me how to make things more
    efficient.
  </p>

  <p>
    Paradoxically, this work has heightened my awareness of what we lose when we
    automate and scale too aggressively or imprecisely, and most of my free time
    on the computer is spent talking and working with people who are thinking
    about how to revitalize online spaces, away from centralized services and
    platforms and on small web sites that are owned by a single person or a
    trusted group. The Indie Web movement is growing on places like Mastodon,
    and it’s a lot of fun to go on internet safaris to people’s little patches
    of web like it’s the 90s again. When I get free time, I like to work on my <a
      href="https://phils-web-site.net">web site</a
    >, where I can really get weird.
  </p>

  <p>
    As generative AI invades the world, I’m experimenting with its utility as a
    pair programming buddy, and looking on with amusement at failed attempts to
    use it to replace genuine human creativity. One reason I spent a lot of time
    on this site was that I wanted to make something that no machine ever could.
  </p>

  <h2>Personal Life</h2>
  <p>I live in Pittsburgh with my wife and daughter and two cats.</p>

  <p>
    I play bass for a band called <a href="https://badcuster.net">Bad Custer</a>
    and occasionally <a href="https://zagways.org">podcast</a> with my friend Jesse.
  </p>
  <style>
    img {
      max-width: 600px;
      width: 100%;
      margin: auto;
      margin-bottom: 4rem;
      border-radius: 1rem;
    }

    p {
      text-align: left;
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
